	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Montreal</placeName> <date>24th June 1866</date>.</p>
				<p>The <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Having heard of <lb/> your recent absence from <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName><lb/> I did not send you any account of<lb/> the celebration of my son&#39;s Minyan<lb/> especially as some had been furnished<lb/> the <placeName>New York</placeName> papers. I do not know<lb/> indeed whether such a celebration<lb/> &#45; always pretty much the same thing&#44;<lb/> its history always repeating itself &#8212; deserves<lb/> place in a monthly &#8212; there was one<lb/> point about it worthy of notice&#44; the<lb/> handsome behavior of the congregation.<lb/> As you know&#44; we are not a large body<lb/> but my son was presented with a<lb/> very nice address &#40;of which I will endeavor<lb/> to enclose you a copy&#41; a valuable</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>gold watch&#44; and a Saving&#39;s Bank<lb/> book with one hundred dollars paid on<lb/> to his Credit.  The celebration was in<lb/> every respect a pleasant one. The<lb/> <add>Hebrew</add> of course read the whole of<lb/> the <add>Hebrew</add> the <add>Hebrew</add> &#38; the <add>Hebrew</add>&#44; and<lb/> was addressed by me thereafter. At<lb/> the breakfast held at my house also<lb/> which was crowded the presentation<lb/> took place&#44; several toasts with<lb/> some good speaking followed &#38;c &#38;c &#38;c &#38;c</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">When is the Jewish<lb/> College going into operation. Would<lb/> it not be well to create at first<lb/> simply a  Faculty of Theology&#44; and<lb/> after having obtained a charter for<lb/> your college&#44; affiliate it to one or<lb/> more universities in order to obtain<lb/> the advantage of their arts courses.<lb/> I am afraid if too much is tried&#44;<lb/> failure will follow &#8212; If I have time<lb/> I will address you in the Occident</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>&#8212;though this is scarcely necessary&#44; the<lb/> matter being in good hands.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Can&#39;t you get a good man<lb/> for <placeName>Charleston</placeName>&#44; a proper&#44; <hi rend="underline">strong</hi> man<lb/> would now check Reform movements<lb/> of the old stamp for the next quarter<lb/> of a century. There is a great want<lb/> of good Portuguese Hazanim. I hope<lb/> the projected college will turn out a<lb/> few.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Do you receive the Hebrew<lb/> periodicals <add>Hebrew</add> or <add>Hebrew</add>  &#8212; I would<lb/> like to see them regularly&#44; and would<lb/> subscribe if I knew where. Should<lb/> you get them &#38; not care to keep<lb/> them&#44; you could let me have<lb/> them occasionally.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Sarah Joseph</persName> told me when<lb/> writing to inquire what she is indebted<lb/> for the Bible. <persName>Mrs. De Sola</persName> unites<lb/> in kind regards &#8212; I am yours truly.<lb/> <persName role="author">Abraham de Sola</persName></p>
		</body>
